    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lessons From an F.B.I. Blunder</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Keith Hansen letter holds prosecution's misstep in Timothy McVeigh case makes one wonder what might be happening in capital cases with lower profile</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The F.B.I.'s Lost Files'' (editorial, May 12): The trial of Timothy J. McVeigh was the most important federal prosecution since the Rosenbergs. The case offered a prominent platform for showing how capital cases could be fairly handled.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The F.B.I.'s Lost Files'' (editorial, May 12): The trial of Timothy J. McVeigh was the most important federal prosecution since the Rosenbergs. The case offered a prominent platform for showing how capital cases could be fairly handled.</p>
        <p>The prosecution had strong evidence, vast public support and nearly unlimited resources. The defendant was lucid, intelligent, unrepentant and represented by effective private counsel. No racial overtones clouded the proceedings. If a case of this significance cannot be handled without a major misstep that comes to light days before the execution, imagine what happens every week in the far less favorable conditions of most capital prosecutions.</p>
        <p>KEITH HANSEN  Princeton, N.J., May 13, 2001</p>
        <p>The writer is a lawyer.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
